Lack enough support: The claim lacks sufficient evidence or data to support the assertion that there was no significant difference in cases when masks were not mandated.
Exist alternative explanation: There could be alternative explanations for the lack of significant difference in cases, such as other preventive measures or factors influencing the spread of the virus.
Contradict fact: The claim contradicts the fact that there was no mask mandate in place during the stay-at-home order in May, which undermines the argument that the absence of a mandate led to no significant difference in cases.
Understate: The claim may understate the potential impact of mask-wearing on reducing COVID-19 transmission by suggesting that there was no significant difference in cases when masks were not mandated.
Exaggerate: The claim may exaggerate the significance of the observed data by implying that it definitively proves the ineffectiveness of masks, when other factors could have influenced the case numbers.
